In 2015, Canada officially elected a new government. The previous Conservative government, under Prime Minister Harper, had maintained the Universal Child Care Benefit (UCCB) and its related tax measures. However, the newly elected Liberal government, under Prime Minister Trudeau, announced significant changes to the UCCB. The key changes include reducing the UCCB payment by half, removing the loyal citizen nod portion, eliminating the GST rebate (a tax credit that provided a maximum rebate of $165), and introducing new tax measures for low- and middle-income families. \\ \end{tabular}
The reduced UCCB payment will provide $320 per month for children under the age of 6. For children between 6 and 17, the benefit remains at $60 per month. This change is expected to provide more targeted support to the most vulnerable children. \\ \end{tabular}
Another significant change includes the introduction of the Canada Child Benefit (CCB), which is a tax-free monthly benefit for low- and middle-income families, up to $45,954 for an individual and $92,208 for a couple with two children. Families with net income over these thresholds will receive a phasing-out of the benefit. \\ \end{tabtable} \\ \end{tabular}
